                        <p style="font-weight:440;font-size:21px;">The purpose of HTML as a language is creating structure. 
                        To enable us to do this, we must learn about creating the <strong>document</strong> using <strong>tags</strong>. 
                        You might be asking: What are tags? <br><br><strong>Tags</strong> are the essential tool which elements are made in. 
                        We will be using and learning many tags throughout the HTML language. 
                        The format goes as following: <br><br> <img height="60" width="255" src="https://i.imgur.com/W4lg7v8.png"> 
                        <br><br> Notice that there is an "opening" tag on the left and a "closing" tag on the right dignified by a "/". Using tags, we can create headings, paragraphs, images, and everything you can thing of.
                        <br><br> Before we dive into writing our own code, we must learn about the "document". The document tells the computer that we are writing in HTML. To do this, we must use tags and create <strong>elements</strong>, which will be nested into each other(tags within tags).
                        <br><br> To create a document, we must create 3 diffrent tags(also called elements). These are: &lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;, &lt;html&gt; &lt;/html&gt;, and &lt;body&gt; &lt;/body&gt;
                        <br><br> Let's go over what each of these means: 
                        <br><br> &lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;: This part of the code always goes on the very top. This tells the document that we are writing in HTML. Notice there are no closing tags: known as an "empty element".
                        <br><br> &lt;html&gt; &lt;/html&gt;: These tags go under the DOCTYPE and defines the whole document.
                        <br><br> &lt;body&gt; &lt;/body&gt;: These tags go inside the html tags and defines the whole body.
                        <br><br> When we write the document, we are also essentially creating the "boiler plate", which you can think of as an empty car frame: 
